Introduction
Human emotions can be directly represented by facial
expressions and emotion profiling.
It is important in today's automation environment, particularly
for any immediate aid in medical or physical emergencies.
Human emotion analysis, like face detection, is a difficult topic
of research in the science of computer vision as well as
machine learning.
Expressions on the face are the fundamental identifiers for
human sentiments, since it is compared to the feelings.
Emotion Detection involves two vital aspects: facial detection
and classifier design.
Face detection relies heavily on extracting the face's feature
points.
Literature review
5
Ajay B S and Madhav Rao proposed Binary neural network based real time
emotion detection on an edge computing device to detect passenger
anomaly in 2021 for passenger safety in public transportation. They used
the LBP algorithm and ML technique. JAFFE dataset was used to train the
model. The accuracy of their project was 81%.
Kairui Guo, Hairong Yu*, Rifai Chai, Hung Nguyen and Steven W. Su
introduced A Hybrid Physiological Approach of Emotional Reaction
Detection Using Combined FCM and SVM Classifier in 2019 . It was a
combination of facial expression and electroencephalogram (EEG)
together to classify the human emotion.
Sivaiah Bellamkonda and N. P. Gopalan gave a Facial Expression
Recognition using Kirsch Edge Detection, LBP and Gabor Wavelets in
2018.It was proposed to improve the performance of FER by using
LBP and Support vector machine (SVM).
They number of dataset like Cohn Kanade, JAFFE, MMI and KDEF to
get the maximum accuracy.
The got 84.17%, 89.67%, 93.00% and 96.00% accuracy for JAFFE,
Cohn Kanade, MMI and KDEF respectively.
Manoj Moolchandani, Shivangi Dwivedi and Samarth Nigam perform
A survey on: Facial Emotion Recognition and Classification in 2021.
It was introduced to compare the various algorithm and strategies to
detect the human emotions. They used LBP and DL algorithm. JAFFE
dataset was taken to check the accuracy of the model.
Proposed work
By writing this survey paper we aim to establish the viability of
Linear Binary Pattern (LBP) and its variants.
We will review the advancements made in LBP and its variants in a
chronological order.
We will also determine which of LBP and its variants have the
highest accuracy and best results.
After the paper is done, we will be able to know the future scope of
LBP and its variants.

Conclusion
Ten papers have been mentioned in the comparison table, stating the
algorithms and tools used in these papers for performing emotion detection .
The LBP feature extraction method is used in the majority of studies. A
Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) is a Deep Learning system that can
take in an input image, assign importance (learnable weights and biases) to
distinct aspects/objects in the image, and distinguish one from the other.
A CNN requires substantially less pre-processing than conventional
classification algorithms and is utilised for background reduction.
The MLP Classifier, which stands for Multi-layer Perceptron
Classifier, and the KNN algorithm were utilised for classification.
For feature extraction, the majority of articles employ LBP.
Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) is a Deep Learning method
that can take in an input image, give importance (learnable weights
and biases) to distinct aspects/objects in the image, and distinguish
one from the other.
A CNN requires substantially less pre-processing than conventional
classification algorithms and is utilised for background reduction. The
MLP Classifier, which stands for Multi-layer Perceptron Classifier,
and the K-NN algorithm were utilised for classification.
Future scope
Future work derived from this research will introduce a method
for detecting emotion from various modalities such as motion
pictures, spoken words, and written text.
Furthermore, the proposed approach's hardware implementation
is a research trend.
Additional machine learning approaches, such as dictionary
learning and semi-supervised learning, can be used to address
this problem.
